In [[theatre]], '''methexis''' ({{lang-grc|μέθεξις}}; also '''methectics'''), is "group sharing". Originating from [[Theatre of ancient Greece|Greek theatre]], the [[audience]] participates, creates and [[improvisation|improvises]] the action of the [[ritual]].

In [[philosophy]], '''methexis''' is the relation between a [[particular]] and a [[Theory of Forms|form]] (in [[Plato]]'s sense), e.g. a beautiful object is said to partake of the form of beauty.<ref>Mautner, Thomas (2005). ''Penguin Dictionary of Philosophy''.{{page needed|date=August 2011}}</ref>

